charity.description:
At Macmillan, we will move mountains to help people with cancer live life as fully as they can.

We’re doing whatever it takes. But without your help we can’t support everyone who needs us. To
donate, volunteer, raise money or campaign with us, call 0300 1000 200 or visit macmillan.org.uk
charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Deborah Tann
story: My brother and I have recently lost our wonderful mum to a brief but brutal battle with lung cancer. She truly was the most special woman in ours and so many other's lives and she will be missed terribly. We would absolutely love it if you could donate any amount to Macmillan Cancer Support, in the hope that we can help other families going through the same to get the support they need.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Manubhai  Patel
story:
In the early morning of 28th January our dada sadly lost his battle to cancer. Today - 13th February is his 80th birthday!

We will forever be grateful for the help and support that Macmillan provided for our grandad and now we would like to help them in his Memory. 

Dada’s love, kindness and generosity will be remembered by all of us, we will cherish all the beautiful memories we have had with him forever. 

On behalf of his whole family, we thank you from the bottom of our hearts for your donations. 

JSK🙏🏼

Name: In memory of Manubhai J Patel

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Jackie Langdon
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

It is with great sadness that we have to announce the passing of Jackie.  She passed away peacefully in hospital on Thursday 11th February. 

Jackie is greatly loved by so many people. 
Jackie’s home was in the Netherlands where she had so many good friends, but her heart always remained with her family back in the UK.  Taking this in to account Jackie will have a private funeral and cremation on Friday 19th February in the Netherlands.  Sadly due to Covid-restrictions her funeral must be kept in close-circle.

Andy will take Jackie home to her family once Covid restrictions allows.

This is obviously a very difficult time for Andy and Jackie’s family back in UK, but they are amazingly close and getting through this together. I know your thoughts and prayers at this time will be very much appreciated by her family.

This page has been set up, if you would like to make a donation to the British Heart Foundation in Jackie's memory.
title: In Loving Memory of Jackie Langdon
Name: In Loving Memory of Jackie Langdon

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Thanks for visiting Emilia’s 24 hour Camp-in page.  She’s raising money for the British Heart Foundation and She’d so grateful for your support. 

She’s having a 24 hour charity camp-in and hopes to raise £50. She says she wants to make a little difference 😍

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Marc  Litchman
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Roy Gadsby
story: I have a family history of heart disease. My dad was diagnosed with coronary artery disease and had a fatal heart attack at the age of 64 when he still had a lot of life to live. Other members of our family have suffered the same but at an even younger age. The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history and  it has led to the budget for research into heart disease being cut in half. Despite  everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends please sponsor me to do this challenge and hopefully prevent more people from dying early unnecessarily.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
I know that giving up chocolate may not seem a big deal, but for those that don't know, I'm disabled and I am physically restricted on what kind of fundraising I can do. I am also a massive chocoholic so this is a challenge for me! 

So why am I supporting the British Heart Foundation (BHF)? 

4 years ago, my dad suffered a heart attack and thanks to the wonderful NHS' care and British Heart Foundation's research, he survived and we got to keep him 💙

I will be forever grateful that we were one of the lucky families and I want to keep raising money to help keep other families together. 

60 years ago, 7 out of 10 heart attacks were fatal. Now 7 out of 10 people survive. Research works. My amazing dad also helped the BHF with research when he was in hospital. 

The pandemic is the biggest challenge the BHF has faced in its 60 year history and it's led to the charity being forced to make the devastating decision to cut its 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, its never needed people like us more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help the BHF keep up the pace of progress. Your donations will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need the BHF most. Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. 

For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story: Anyone that knows me well knows how much I love my chocolate but I have decided to give it it from the 1st of March till the 31st of March please support me in this and please give what you can thank you! Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Michael Fairman
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Andrew  Tait
story:
I am taking the plunge and cutting out chocolate for the whole of March ,My friends and family all no how much of a chocoholic i am so this will be the hardest thing i have ever done !!. Loosing my amazing Dad to a heart attack & not knowing he had heart Disease the BHF has a big place in my heart , If i can do a small part to help other people fight through so

Many  heart problems then it will be worth it .

All the donations will help this amazing foundation 

The pandemic is the biggest challenge the British Heart foundation have faced in there 60 year history. And it's led to them being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budgets in half. So the truth is, they have never needed people like us more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help BHF keep  up the pace of progress. My willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
eventName: WBCC Club Night for Guide Dogs
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. 

Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
In the UK today, almost two million people are living with sight loss and of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone. Many suffer from depression and struggle with feelings of isolation.

Guide Dogs is here to help solve this problem. We provide individual support that overcomes the emotional and physical challenges faced by people living with sight loss.

We work for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life. We work for a world where blind people no longer feel invisible, where the quality of their eye sight is genuinely the only difference between them and the rest of society.

A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling your needs and dreams. A world where being blind or partially sighted isn't what defines you.

eventName: Aaron's Week Long Stream for Great Ormond Street Hospital
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Hi Everyone,

I'd like to announce that I'm doing another charity stream. This time my chosen charity will be Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity.

While I may not have a personal attachment to this charity in particular, the work that they do is incredibly important. This is a charity I can fully support and get behind because if for what ever reason my nieces or my friends and relatives children need the care this hospital provides, then I hope mine and your contributions will help support this charity to carry on creating miracles in helping many sick and seriously ill children.

I have been wanting to do another charity stream so I thought why not do it one year on from my last one. I have decided to stick to my last streams format of an AGDQ/SGDQ based format where they do themed blocks i.e. Disney Block, Bad Games Block, Sonic Block etc. 

I plan to stream on my Twitch channel over 7 days (not continuously) and play certain games on certain days, starting from Monday 1st March 2021 through to Sunday 7th March 2021. My goal is the same as my previous two streams, to raise £300 and if I raise any more than that, it’ll be bonus.

If you could head on over to my twitch channel beforehand, click follow and turn notifications on, that way you’ll get notified when I’m live. If you don't have a Twitch account it's relatively simple to set up an account. If you could share this around it'd be appreciated.

Thank you all for taking the time to read this and I hope to see you all there!

Donation Page: https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/streamforgosh

When: Monday 1st March - Sunday 7th March

All Random All Monday - League of Legends ARAMs

TFT Tuesday - Teamfight Tactics

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Zena Wells
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit Zena’s JustGiving page.

As a family we’ve decided, instead of flowers for her funeral, we wanted to raise money for GOSH.

As some may know, Mum had a severely compromised immune system which was something she was born with. It meant she was poorly a lot and it took her longer to fight off your average cold.

GOSH do really important research, including into genetic conditions and immunology so we thought it was apt that they benefitted from our tragic loss.

Mum worked with children all her life, and was dedicated to helping them in every way she could. We miss her dearly but knowing GOSH will be able to carry on their vital work as a result brings us just a little bit of comfort.

- Gemma, Kirsty and Graham

charity.description: We fundraise to enhance Great Ormond Street Hospital’s ability to transform the health and wellbeing of children and young people. Donations help to fund advanced medical equipment, child and family support services, pioneering research and rebuilding and refurbishment.
charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Thank you for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I was first taken into the care of Great Ormond Street Hospital for Children at 20 months old, due to kidney failure, after seeking treatment at 2 different hospitals beforehand. Shortly after arriving at the hospital, I was diagnosed with a rare kidney condition called cystinuria. My kidneys were completely blocked with cystine stones causing them to fail. Ever since then, I have been under the fantastic care of GOSH, I have had over 10 successful surgeries in my time there, and they have never failed to provide me with the mental and physical support when I was struggling. Sadly, as I approach the age of 18 it's time for me to leave GOSH and begin care in an adult hospital. Not only did Great Ormond Street save my life, they provided the care and support for my family and allowed me to live like any regular child, continuing the things I love to do. It has felt like a second home to me since I was young and I will always be grateful for the hardworking, affectionate team at GOSH, who provide not only treatment, but a place that feels like home to seriously ill children.

So, as a patient myself, and someone who has lived the GOSH experience, I'd like to push myself out of my comfort zone in order to raise money for this incredible hospital and to support future children like myself. Over the course of March 2021, I will be running 100 miles and recording my progress here, if you would like to contribute in any way, I would appreciate it very much.

For more information, please feel free to contact me at:

skyemae@icloud.com

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Kay Egginton
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

This page has been set up in loving memory of Kay Marie Egginton.  

Kay was taken from us far too soon and our hearts have been left completely broken.  She was the most kind and selfless person and will be truly missed.  She was always smiling and really did light up any room she entered. She was always a pleasure to be around. She was fun, often unintentionally hilarious and simply the most wonderful person. Our lives will never be the same without her and the world will be a little less bright without her beautiful smile.

Without a doubt, Kay was the most beautiful soul to ever grace this earth.  She was so brave, incredibly strong and we will forever be proud of the fight she gave.

In lieu of flowers at her funeral the family asks for any donations to go to Cancer Research, a cause close to all our hearts.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Ken Lindsay
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my Just Giving page. 

I recently lost my brother Ken to covid. Since his death, I have found out that he had been told that he had untreatable cancer of unknown origin. Unfortunately, he was too frail to have the tests that would have confirmed this diagnosis and too ill to receive treatment.

Cancer has touched me so many times in my life. I have had it myself. It took my dad, my mom, my aunt, my father-in-law and two close family friends and it would undoubtedly have taken my brother had he survived covid. 

Cancer treatment has improved over the years, but we are still a long way from eradicating this insidious disease. Please make a donation, in memory of my lovely brother,  as much or as little as you can afford, to help in the fight to make cancer history.

Thank you

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk.

We are raising money for marie curie as my grandad lost his battle to lung cancer in march 2020. Marie curie team was helping our family look after him from home, but beacause of covid we couldn't get the donation we wanted to, so we thought about doing this 24 hour live stream. It will be streamed on our facebook page Ladida Gaming

charity.name: Marie Curie
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Vincent Lamb
story:
In Loving Memory of Vincent Lamb

Vincent sadly passed away on the 5th of February 2021 surrounded by his wife Maureen, and his children Rebecca, Rachael and Nathan.  He was intelligent, funny, kind and generous and had an impact on everyone he met.  He will be missed by all who knew him.

Vincent developed Progressive Supranuclear Palsy in 2015 which he fought courageously. Sadly, it affected his speech and mobility. Marie Curie Day Therapies Unit in Edinburgh had a huge impact on Vince and our family’s quality of life over the last two years.

Vince enjoyed attending his Friday day therapies group with Maureen until lockdown struck. The day therapies team continued to be involved in Vince’s life. Each week he enjoyed online relaxation sessions, coffee mornings, reiki sessions with Laure and weekly chats with Debbie.  As well as this, he had a dedicated team of multidisciplinary professionals who we could call for anything and they would help - from getting a stairlift installed to counselling.

We will be forever grateful to the Marie Curie Day Therapies team - Debbie, Gail, David, Ruth, Aaron, Stefi, Kim, and all the volunteers especially Sheila, Mike and Joan - for the kindness and support they showed Vince and our family.

story:
To mark A.S Watson's 180th anniversary, Superdrug are launching a new 180 Challenge this February to help raise vital funds for Marie Curie nurses 🌟

The challenge is simple: take on any activity to do with the number 180, 18, or 1.8 this February and raise £180 to fund a night of crucial Marie Curie nursing care 

All stores on area 61 are taking part in either individual or group challenges, check out stores social medias to see what challenges are being completed!

Please note on your donations which store you are sponsoring.

With healthcare services at breaking point, our care has never been more critical. Your support will keep our nurses on the frontline, providing vital end of life care and emotional support to families facing the toughest of times.

Your support will keep their nurses on the frontline, delivering vital end of life care and emotional support to more families in need

charity.name: Marie Curie
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Thank you for visiting our Just Giving Page.

Falmouth Lifeboat Station covers the coastline between Dodman Point and Black Head and includes both the Fal and Helford Estuaries. The station has a Severn Class All Weather Lifeboat and an Atlantic 85 class Inshore Lifeboat which launch on service over a hundred times each year. Our volunteer crew are available 24/7 for anyone who needs our help and we will always be there to answer that call.

Keeping a modern fleet of lifeboats maintained, fuelled and ever ready to go to the rescue from all 33 South West lifeboat stations is expensive and we rely entirely on voluntary donations to ensure this service is maintained. Add to that crew training and kit, and the pounds start to add up. It costs an average of £158k to Run lifeboat stations in the South West but this year, with the implications of Covid-19, we haven’t been able to fundraise to keep our lifeboats afloat.

We rely on donations from you the public to continue saving lives at sea - your donation to this page will help support the running costs of stations in the South West including our lifeboats based in Falmouth and their volunteer crew.
title: RNLI South West Region Lifesavers Fund
Name: RNLI South West Region Lifesavers Fund

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
I am taking part in the Cornwall RNLI virtual challenge 2021 to help support the RNLI's volunteer crews in saving lives around our coast. The Challenge is to complete a Run, Walk, Cycle, or Swim over the period between 1st February to 31st March. The distance can be between two or more Cornish Lifeboat Stations, picking the distance that best suits and it can be carried out anywhere, be that a garden, park, swimming pool or even a treadmill. I will run/ walk the distance between Padstow to Newquay, and Newquay to St Agnes life boat stations, in addition to any other distance I can cover within the time period. Thank you in advance for any support! 

There are a total of 13 RNLI lifeboat stations around the coast of Cornwall, from Bude to Looe with the total overall distance is 228 miles. Bude to Port Isaac = 30 miles Port Isaac to Rock = 9 miles Rock to Padstow 17 miles Padstow to Newquay = 15 miles Newquay to St Agnes = 13 miles St Agnes to St Ives = 21 miles St Ives to Sennen = 17 miles Sennen to Penlee = 8 miles Penlee to Lizard = 25 miles Lizard to Falmouth = 21 miles Falmouth to Fowey = 33 miles Fowey to Looe = 19 miles

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story: Dan and I went for a 10 mile walk in the snow today from Franchise, the farm where my dad works. Along the way, we thought about what was happening to other children around the world, who perhaps have lost parents due to Covid-19 and we wondered what we could do to help them. We looked to see what Unicef was doing when we got home and we decided that we would like to support their global vaccination drive. Unicef aim to deliver 2 billion Covid-19 vaccines for health workers and the most high risk people on our planet. By keeping their carers and health workers safe, it will in turn help to keep the most vulnerable children safe. £44 will supply 25 doses of Covid-19 vaccines. We plan to walk one hundred miles in the 9 days over half term across different routes from Franchise farm. Please can you take a minute to donate how ever little. Every little counts!!! Thank you so much, Charlotte and Dan x

ProfileWhy: we want to help other children around the world !

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
eventName: St Augustine’s Virtual Walk to Jerusalem for WaterAid during Lent
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Each year St Augustine's pledges to raise money for charity in UK and abroad. This year for our international challenge we have chosen WaterAid.

We all tend to take water for granted in the UK but right now there are over 800 million people who don't have access to clean water and over two billion people lack a decent toilet. At St Augustine's we are asking as many people as possible to join us on a Virtual Walk to Jerusalem for the 44 days of Lent. We will be counting together the miles everyone walks each day when doing their daily exercise. Every Sunday, the total will be announced in church, posted on our website (http://www.staugustinespringfield.org.uk )and on here. 

Our aim is that together over the 44 days of Lent that we will walk the 2761 miles and reach Jerusalem by Easter.

We have an ambitious target - £1380 which is equivalent to 50p per mile.

TOGETHER WITH YOUR HELP WE WILL DO IT!
title: St Augustine Virtual Walk to Jerusalem for WaterAid during Lent

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.

With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.
